Figures out today by Statistics South Africa show housing and utility costs rose 4.9% year on year. JOHANNESBURG - Latest data shows that inflation remains unchanged at 4.5 percent in June compared to May. This came as a slight disappointment amid the hope that the Reserve Bank may deliver a second interest rate cut in the coming months.
The main contributor to the inflation rate was housing and utilities. READ: Reserve Bank slashes repo rate These costs increased to 4.9 percent year-on-year. Economists have pointed to slowing wage growth and a sluggish local economy as reasons. A stable rand and the expectation that inflation will remain contained has raised hopes that South Africa will get more interest rate cuts, following the 25 basis point cut in July.